WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.440
You know, if I asked you right now to tell me the exact difference between a wink and a blink,

00:05.120 --> 00:08.640
you would probably think I was setting up some terrible dad joke.

00:08.880 --> 00:11.160
Right, yeah, like there's a punchline coming.

00:11.480 --> 00:11.880
Exactly.

00:12.280 --> 00:17.420
You'd probably say something along the lines of, well, I mean, I wink, but a blink just sort of,

00:17.580 --> 00:19.080
it just happens on its own.

00:19.540 --> 00:26.980
Like one is this deliberate choice you make on purpose to, you know, signal a friend across a

00:26.980 --> 00:34.000
crowded room, and the other is just a reflex, just an automatic biological function to keep

00:34.000 --> 00:35.480
your eyeball from drying out.

00:35.700 --> 00:39.440
Yeah, it seems like the most obvious, simple distinction in the world, right?

00:39.480 --> 00:39.840
Totally.

00:40.200 --> 00:43.920
But the wild thing is, and this really blew my mind when we started looking into this,

00:44.880 --> 00:50.900
determining the exact rigorous boundary between a wink and a blink, like between an action and a

00:50.900 --> 00:56.780
mere physical event, it's actually one of the most notoriously difficult unsolved problems

00:56.780 --> 01:00.420
in the entire history of science and philosophy.

01:00.780 --> 01:01.460
Oh, absolutely.

01:01.820 --> 01:07.480
And I mean, it sounds absurd until you realize the actual stakes involved.

01:07.480 --> 01:14.880
This isn't just some academic puzzle for people in tweed jackets arguing in like university lounges.

01:15.340 --> 01:16.300
Think about a courtroom.

01:16.820 --> 01:21.920
When jurors are sitting in a murder trial, they don't just look at a deceased victim and say,

01:22.540 --> 01:26.560
well, the body has ceased biological function, case closed.

01:26.780 --> 01:27.140
Right.

01:27.300 --> 01:28.260
That would be insane.

01:28.380 --> 01:28.820
Exactly.

01:29.400 --> 01:34.800
They are specifically tasked with figuring out the intent behind the physical event.

01:35.200 --> 01:38.320
Was it a premeditated first degree murder?

01:38.660 --> 01:39.760
Was it an accident?

01:39.960 --> 01:40.900
You know, manslaughter?

01:41.460 --> 01:45.820
Did the defendant pull the trigger on purpose, executing this planned action?

01:46.100 --> 01:51.760
Or did a loud noise startle them and cause an involuntary muscle spasm in their finger?

01:52.220 --> 01:52.580
Wow.

01:52.580 --> 01:55.260
Yeah, when you frame it like that, it's huge.

01:55.400 --> 01:55.840
It is.

01:55.900 --> 02:02.100
Our entire legal system, our whole framework for moral judgments, guilt, innocence,

02:02.100 --> 02:10.540
all of it rests completely on this incredibly shadowy, undefined border between voluntary action and involuntary behavior.

02:10.900 --> 02:13.300
So that is our mission for this deep dive.

02:13.300 --> 02:20.940
We are going to completely deconstruct how human beings actually act, how we emote, and how we make decisions.

02:21.060 --> 02:21.240
Yeah.

02:21.360 --> 02:25.600
And to do that, we really have to throw out centuries of completely outdated science.

02:25.820 --> 02:26.380
We do.

02:26.640 --> 02:26.860
Yeah.

02:27.020 --> 02:30.460
We are pulling from two intensely fascinating sources today.

02:30.460 --> 02:42.800
The first is Alicia Guerrero's Dynamics in Action, which just completely dismantles how philosophers and scientists have thought about cause and effect in human behavior.

02:42.980 --> 02:45.160
It really tears the whole foundation down.

02:45.160 --> 03:03.980
And the second is this cutting-edge paper, From Catharsis to Geometric Bayesianism, RSVP and Demise of the Hydraulic Model of Emotion, which, and this is crazy, uses physics and math to prove why venting your anger is actually making you worse.

03:03.980 --> 03:15.100
Yes. The overarching theme we really have to confront here is that for hundreds of years, humanity has relied on these mechanical metaphors to understand the mind.

03:15.500 --> 03:15.680
Right.

03:15.960 --> 03:25.600
We've treated the brain like a complex clockwork mechanism with gears and springs, or later on, like a pressure cooker holding back volatile fluids.

03:25.680 --> 03:26.740
The old Freudian thing.

03:26.820 --> 03:27.260
Exactly.

03:27.260 --> 03:38.920
But what the most recent breakthroughs in physics and biology are showing us is that treating the human brain and behavior like a highly sensitive, constantly shifting weather system is vastly more accurate.

03:39.460 --> 03:43.640
A weather system. I love that. I really want to hold on to that image.

03:43.900 --> 03:44.080
Yeah.

03:44.180 --> 03:47.480
But before we get to the weather, we have to start with the clockwork.

03:47.620 --> 03:48.680
Yeah, we have to go back.

03:49.040 --> 03:53.960
Way back. We need to figure out how we got it so catastrophically wrong in the first place.

03:53.960 --> 03:58.940
And that takes us back, like, 2,500 years to ancient Greece.

03:59.920 --> 04:01.780
It all begins with Aristotle.

04:02.260 --> 04:03.720
Good old Aristotle.

04:04.060 --> 04:10.980
Right. He established this fundamental rule of physics that has essentially haunted philosophy and science ever since.

04:11.220 --> 04:14.740
He stated that nothing can move or cause itself.

04:15.060 --> 04:18.540
And, I mean, you really have to put yourself in Aristotle's shoes for a second.

04:18.540 --> 04:23.580
He was trying to build a coherent framework for how change happens in the universe.

04:23.960 --> 04:25.780
Right. He's just looking around at rocks and stuff.

04:25.880 --> 04:33.800
Exactly. He was observing the natural world, the mechanics of everyday life, and he established what seemed like an airtight principle.

04:34.440 --> 04:38.660
If a stone is rolling down a hill, something had to have pushed it.

04:38.760 --> 04:39.360
Makes sense.

04:39.660 --> 04:39.940
Right.

04:39.940 --> 04:44.660
A physical object cannot spontaneously act upon itself.

04:45.860 --> 04:49.920
One part of a system has to impart force onto another part.

04:50.240 --> 04:54.280
It sounds completely logical, almost undeniable.

04:54.720 --> 04:56.840
Until you look at anything that's actually alive.

04:56.960 --> 04:57.280
Tingo.

04:57.280 --> 05:09.920
It creates this monumental, system-breaking headache the absolute second you try to apply that rule to living, breathing organisms.

05:10.320 --> 05:13.720
Because organisms clearly constantly move themselves.

05:14.120 --> 05:22.400
There is this wild medical story from the 1950s that illustrates this exact philosophical terror perfectly.

05:22.580 --> 05:24.180
Oh, I know the one you're talking about.

05:24.180 --> 05:25.200
It's so creepy.

05:25.980 --> 05:29.480
There was this pioneering neurosurgeon named Wilder Penfield.

05:30.020 --> 05:34.640
He was performing surgeries on awake patients who suffered from severe epilepsy.

05:35.060 --> 05:37.760
Awake brain surgery is always a wild concept.

05:37.980 --> 05:38.200
Yeah.

05:38.480 --> 05:39.000
Terrifying.

05:39.000 --> 05:49.960
So to find the source of the seizures, he would open their skulls, expose their brains, and use this tiny electrical probe to literally poke specific areas of the cortex.

05:50.180 --> 05:50.600
Right.

05:50.840 --> 05:58.700
He would stimulate the motor cortex, and suddenly the patient would raise their arm, or their hand would clench, or they would just blurt out a random vowel sound.

05:59.340 --> 06:03.240
But the profound part is what the patient said when he did this.

06:03.240 --> 06:05.700
They never claimed ownership of the movement.

06:06.100 --> 06:06.460
Never.

06:06.940 --> 06:08.480
They would immediately protest.

06:08.700 --> 06:12.600
They'd look at the surgeon in an absolute panic and say, I didn't do that.

06:12.700 --> 06:14.040
You pulled that out of me.

06:14.420 --> 06:17.120
Or they'd say, my arm moved, but I didn't move it.

06:17.160 --> 06:18.520
Which is deeply unsettling.

06:18.640 --> 06:18.980
Totally.

06:19.420 --> 06:20.620
Their muscles contracted.

06:20.860 --> 06:22.380
Their vocal cords vibrated.

06:22.380 --> 06:28.860
The biological mechanism worked flawlessly, but they felt absolutely zero internal agency.

06:29.900 --> 06:32.420
From the outside, it looked like an action.

06:32.800 --> 06:35.640
From the inside, it was just an event happening to them.

06:35.680 --> 06:37.200
It was a blink, not a wink.

06:37.200 --> 06:42.140
Which perfectly encapsulates Aristotle's dilemma regarding the origin of movement.

06:43.060 --> 06:50.300
If Wilder Penfield's electrical probe is what causes the arm to rise, the origin of the movement is clearly external.

06:50.300 --> 06:53.120
It is an alien force acting upon the body.

06:53.840 --> 06:56.900
Aristotle would categorize that as compulsory behavior.

06:57.160 --> 06:58.360
You are being pushed.

06:59.320 --> 07:01.640
But what happens when we act voluntarily?

07:02.120 --> 07:10.980
Aristotle actually spent a lot of time analyzing situations where the line between voluntary and compulsory gets dangerously blurry.

07:11.160 --> 07:11.360
Yeah.

07:11.520 --> 07:13.560
He had a really great thought experiment for this, right?

07:13.580 --> 07:14.180
He did.

07:14.180 --> 07:20.060
He presented this famous scenario of a ship captain caught in a massive storm.

07:20.300 --> 07:25.340
I want to paint the picture of this because it's so incredibly relatable even today.

07:26.060 --> 07:30.300
You have this merchant captain sailing a heavy ship across the agency.

07:31.080 --> 07:33.680
A sudden, violent squall hits.

07:33.940 --> 07:36.000
The waves are crashing over the deck.

07:36.380 --> 07:38.540
The ship is taking on water fast.

07:38.980 --> 07:41.160
And it's on the verge of capsizing.

07:41.220 --> 07:42.000
You're ready for a death.

07:42.000 --> 07:42.560
Exactly.

07:43.040 --> 07:48.060
So to stop the ship from sinking, the captain makes a split-second decision.

07:48.420 --> 07:54.360
He orders the crew to throw all their incredibly valuable cargo overboard into the ocean.

07:54.520 --> 07:56.140
All his wealth just gone.

07:56.340 --> 07:56.680
Right.

07:57.020 --> 08:01.940
Now the storm passes, the ship survives, and they limp back to port.

08:01.940 --> 08:11.640
If you approach that captain and ask, hey, did you throw your livelihood into the sea voluntarily, the captain would probably look at you like you were insane.

08:11.880 --> 08:12.100
Right.

08:12.160 --> 08:12.920
He'd be furious.

08:13.300 --> 08:14.240
He'd say, of course not.

08:14.300 --> 08:15.960
I didn't want to ruin myself financially.

08:16.100 --> 08:17.760
I was forced to do it by the storm.

08:17.920 --> 08:22.560
But Aristotle steps in here and examines the actual mechanics of the event.

08:22.940 --> 08:24.900
Was the captain actually forced?

08:24.900 --> 08:31.700
Did the wind physically grab the captain's hands and compel him to heave the crates over the rail?

08:32.140 --> 08:32.420
No.

08:32.800 --> 08:36.780
The origin of the physical movement was still entirely within the captain.

08:37.800 --> 08:40.460
Aristotle categorizes this as a mixed action.

08:41.320 --> 08:43.080
It is undoubtedly painful.

08:43.480 --> 08:45.580
It is done under extreme duress.

08:45.900 --> 08:49.280
And it goes completely against his long-term desires.

08:49.620 --> 08:49.960
Right.

08:49.960 --> 09:01.800
But at the exact microscopic moment the choice was made, throwing the cargo was the most rational, appropriate thing to do to achieve his immediate goal, which was survival.

09:02.200 --> 09:04.740
The principle of movement was internal.

09:05.260 --> 09:07.440
The captain perceived a deadly threat.

09:07.880 --> 09:10.600
He possessed a profound desire to stay alive.

09:10.780 --> 09:14.000
And that internal desire is what moved his physical body.

09:14.520 --> 09:17.280
But here's where Aristotle kind of traps himself.

09:17.420 --> 09:17.640
Yeah.

09:17.640 --> 09:26.520
Because of his own unbreakable rule that absolutely nothing can move itself, he had to engage in some truly staggering mental gymnastics here.

09:26.640 --> 09:27.440
He really did.

09:27.520 --> 09:29.680
He couldn't just say the captain moved himself.

09:29.940 --> 09:33.640
He basically had to conceptually slice the organism in half.

09:34.060 --> 09:39.140
He argued that the animal's soul, or its core desire, acts this unmoved mover.

09:39.360 --> 09:39.660
Yeah.

09:39.800 --> 09:42.380
The soul reaches out toward a specific goal in the environment.

09:42.380 --> 09:51.120
It's like a ghost driving a meat suit.

09:51.120 --> 09:51.720
Exactly.

09:51.720 --> 09:57.920
So, technically, in Aristotle's framework, the soul is pushing the body.

09:57.920 --> 10:06.600
It is two separate parts interacting, which magically preserves his rule that a single unified thing is not moving itself.

10:06.600 --> 10:17.840
And that artificial split between the desiring soul and the mechanical body, that is the foundational crack in our whole understanding of human behavior.

10:17.840 --> 10:26.660
Because if you flash forward a couple of thousand years to the Enlightenment and the scientific revolution, modern science enters the chat.

10:26.660 --> 10:27.600
With a vengeance.

10:28.020 --> 10:28.240
Right.

10:28.440 --> 10:31.820
Isaac Newton formulates his monumental laws of physics.

10:32.620 --> 10:40.440
Post-Newtonian philosophy looks back at Aristotle and says, hey, we agree with your fundamental rule that nothing moves itself.

10:40.860 --> 10:43.380
That aligns perfectly with our new physics.

10:43.840 --> 10:48.840
But we're absolutely throwing out this mystical idea of the soul reaching toward a goal.

10:48.840 --> 10:51.920
They completely purged the universe of purpose.

10:52.140 --> 10:52.480
They did.

10:52.840 --> 10:57.480
Aristotle originally had four different types of causes to explain why things happen.

10:58.100 --> 11:07.040
He had final cause, which was the ultimate goal or purpose of an action, and formal cause, which was the underlying structure or pattern of a thing.

11:07.320 --> 11:09.600
But Newtonian physics was ruthless.

11:09.900 --> 11:10.600
Oh, completely.

11:11.220 --> 11:16.500
It stripped everything down to just one acceptable type of causality, efficient cause.

11:16.500 --> 11:20.820
This is the ultimate billiard ball model of the universe.

11:21.060 --> 11:25.380
Reality is nothing but tiny inert atoms crashing into each other.

11:25.500 --> 11:27.060
Just dead matter bumping around.

11:27.180 --> 11:27.440
Right.

11:27.940 --> 11:29.940
A cue ball strikes an eight ball.

11:30.120 --> 11:34.840
The kinetic energy transfers in a split second, and the eight ball rolls away.

11:35.700 --> 11:41.040
The universe is just a giant, meaningless, mathematically predictable game of pool.

11:41.040 --> 11:47.620
Everything that happens is merely the result of external forces bumping into dead matter.

11:47.860 --> 11:50.920
Okay, let's stop and really look at the implications of that.

11:51.060 --> 11:51.240
Okay.

11:51.400 --> 11:52.820
Because it's actually crazy.

11:53.320 --> 11:59.280
If we are forced to view the human brain and the human body like a cue stick hitting a cue ball,

11:59.720 --> 12:04.380
how on earth do we explain the most basic realities of human existence?

12:04.560 --> 12:05.860
It gets really difficult.

12:06.100 --> 12:06.320
Right.

12:06.320 --> 12:08.520
How do we explain long-term planning?

12:08.760 --> 12:12.560
Let's say I make a decision today that I want to become a neurosurgeon.

12:13.280 --> 12:18.200
That intention has to somehow guide my daily actions for the next 15 years.

12:18.800 --> 12:25.140
I have to study, take exams, skip parties, apply to medical school, and survive residency.

12:25.400 --> 12:27.260
That's a lot of sustained action.

12:27.260 --> 12:28.260
Exactly.

12:28.980 --> 12:36.260
But a cue stick doesn't follow the ball down the felt table to continuously guide it around obstacles

12:36.260 --> 12:38.800
and gently shepherd it into the corner pocket.

12:39.200 --> 12:46.200
It just transfers its energy in one violent split second collision and immediately disconnects.

12:46.460 --> 12:53.500
The friction you are feeling right now is the exact fatal flaw of the modern theory of causality.

12:53.500 --> 12:58.540
In philosophical terms, we refer to this as the bump-and-run model.

12:58.900 --> 12:59.420
Bump-and-run.

12:59.460 --> 12:59.680
Yeah.

13:00.200 --> 13:03.040
Modern science basically built a trap for itself.

13:03.720 --> 13:10.440
By permanently banning the concept of self-cause and by completely outlawing the idea of a standing,

13:10.940 --> 13:17.480
top-down constraint, like a conscious goal that continuously oversees and guides a complex system

13:17.480 --> 13:24.360
over time, they left themselves with no vocabulary to explain how an intention actually sustains an action.

13:24.720 --> 13:25.720
They just threw it out.

13:25.840 --> 13:26.640
They had to.

13:26.900 --> 13:31.320
They were forced to imagine a human intention as nothing more than a mental cue stick.

13:31.320 --> 13:37.140
It flares up, it strikes the motor neurons, the muscles twitch, and the intention instantly disengages,

13:37.620 --> 13:40.280
leaving the body to blindly carry out the momentum.

13:40.280 --> 13:47.540
Which is obviously demonstrably false to absolutely anyone who has ever lived a human life.

13:48.120 --> 13:54.180
I mean, if I am threading a needle, my intention to thread that needle is actively managing the

13:54.180 --> 13:57.420
micro-tremors in my fingers every single millisecond.

13:57.780 --> 13:59.580
It's not a one-time push.

13:59.900 --> 14:00.420
Exactly.

14:00.420 --> 14:07.580
But instead of realizing their mechanical billiard ball model was broken, scientists and philosophers

14:07.580 --> 14:11.920
in the early 20th century decided to just double down.

14:12.120 --> 14:13.660
They really dug their heels in.

14:13.800 --> 14:14.400
They did.

14:14.540 --> 14:19.540
If the mind didn't fit the physics, they decided to just throw the mind in the garbage.

14:20.000 --> 14:24.880
And that leads us directly into the incredibly bizarre era of behaviorism.

14:24.980 --> 14:25.440
Oh man.

14:25.960 --> 14:26.480
Behaviorism?

14:26.480 --> 14:32.000
Yeah, behaviorism was really an act of desperation because researchers couldn't figure out how

14:32.000 --> 14:38.320
a mental intention, this invisible weightless ghost in the machine, could possibly push physical

14:38.320 --> 14:41.820
heavy muscles without violating the conservation of energy.

14:42.440 --> 14:46.120
They just decided that the internal mind was scientifically irrelevant.

14:46.340 --> 14:46.940
Just ignore it?

14:46.980 --> 14:47.460
Pretty much.

14:47.800 --> 14:53.560
They leaned heavily on the philosopher David Hume, specifically his concept of constant conjunction.

14:53.960 --> 14:55.980
Right, Hume was like the ultimate skeptic.

14:55.980 --> 15:00.300
He basically argued that humans can't actually see causality.

15:01.040 --> 15:04.380
We can never observe the invisible force of cause and effect.

15:05.380 --> 15:10.820
All we can actually observe is one event happening followed immediately by another event.

15:10.940 --> 15:13.580
Over and over, event A, then event B.

15:14.040 --> 15:16.620
A bell rings and a dog drools.

15:17.180 --> 15:22.940
We assume the bell caused the drool, but strictly speaking, we only see the conjunction of the two

15:22.940 --> 15:23.380
events.

15:23.380 --> 15:26.160
So the behaviorists took this and ran with it.

15:26.240 --> 15:29.200
They said, stop worrying about what the dog is thinking.

15:29.400 --> 15:31.300
Stop worrying about the ghost in the machine.

15:32.040 --> 15:36.220
Science is only about observable inputs and observable outputs.

15:37.220 --> 15:38.380
Stimulus and response.

15:39.160 --> 15:42.740
Which leads to a terrifying definition of human life if you think about it.

15:42.740 --> 15:49.560
Under strict behaviorism, human action is reduced to nothing more than uttering the correct sequence

15:49.560 --> 15:55.660
of words or executing the correct sequence of physical movements under suitable environmental

15:55.660 --> 15:56.460
circumstances.

15:57.100 --> 15:57.600
That's it.

15:58.300 --> 15:59.840
Intent is a total myth.

16:00.020 --> 16:02.220
It completely erases the inner life.

16:02.560 --> 16:03.140
It does.

16:03.140 --> 16:05.800
There was this philosopher, J.L.

16:05.880 --> 16:11.020
Austin, who really championed this with his performative theory of action.

16:12.080 --> 16:18.220
He argued that certain massive life events, like getting married, are not about your internal

16:18.220 --> 16:21.540
emotional state or your conscious intentions at all.

16:21.600 --> 16:21.860
Right.

16:21.920 --> 16:27.420
Getting married is simply the physical act of uttering a specific script of words in a specific

16:27.420 --> 16:29.340
socially recognized setting.

16:29.340 --> 16:37.640
But when you try to apply this theory to the real world, it results in absolute comical disaster.

16:38.080 --> 16:42.320
There are two incredible examples from the text that highlight this perfectly.

16:42.480 --> 16:44.340
Oh, these examples are so good.

16:44.460 --> 16:45.040
They're crazy.

16:45.520 --> 16:49.860
So the first is a scenario about a woman, let's just call her Hannah.

16:50.360 --> 16:52.000
Hannah is at a lively party.

16:52.160 --> 16:55.640
She's having a few drinks, laughing, joking around with her friends.

16:55.640 --> 17:01.540
A guy at the party, completely playing along with the joke, slides a ring onto her finger

17:01.540 --> 17:06.120
and jokingly recites an ancient traditional Jewish wedding phrase.

17:06.380 --> 17:07.240
Just goofing off.

17:07.360 --> 17:07.620
Right.

17:07.920 --> 17:09.260
Everyone in the circle is laughing.

17:09.400 --> 17:10.360
The guy knows it's a joke.

17:10.480 --> 17:11.520
Hannah knows it's a joke.

17:12.240 --> 17:17.620
But sitting quietly on the couch nearby is an actual rabbi who happens to be a strict

17:17.620 --> 17:19.340
expert in rabbinical law.

17:19.420 --> 17:19.900
Yes.

17:19.900 --> 17:26.860
The rabbi stands up, walks over, and says, excuse me, all the objective conditions for

17:26.860 --> 17:28.240
a marriage were just met.

17:28.960 --> 17:34.780
A ring of value was presented, the correct words were spoken flawlessly, and there are

17:34.780 --> 17:36.260
valid witnesses present.

17:37.080 --> 17:42.660
Regardless of your internal feelings, by the letter of the law, you two are now officially

17:42.660 --> 17:44.040
legally married.

17:44.040 --> 17:49.000
It perfectly highlights the absolute absurdity of ignoring intent.

17:49.540 --> 17:52.920
And the crazy thing is, it's not just the theoretical party trick.

17:53.140 --> 17:56.540
It happens in the real world with devastating consequences.

17:56.800 --> 17:57.020
Yes.

17:57.140 --> 18:01.000
The second example is an actual documented news story from Pakistan.

18:01.820 --> 18:07.160
A real-life husband and wife were working as actors on a television soap opera.

18:07.600 --> 18:11.960
They were on set, the cameras were rolling, and they were playing their fictional characters.

18:12.180 --> 18:13.640
They're literally doing a job.

18:13.640 --> 18:14.040
Right.

18:14.280 --> 18:19.620
During a highly dramatic scene, the script called for the husband to recite the traditional

18:19.620 --> 18:23.640
Islamic divorce declaration saying, I divorce you three times.

18:24.120 --> 18:25.220
They're acting.

18:25.680 --> 18:29.220
They're on a soundstage surrounded by boom mics and lighting raves.

18:29.240 --> 18:30.500
But the words were said.

18:30.640 --> 18:31.260
Exactly.

18:32.020 --> 18:37.840
A group of strict religious clerics watched the broadcast and issued a real-life ruling.

18:38.560 --> 18:43.480
They stated that because the specific words were articulated, the real-life

18:43.480 --> 18:47.220
marriage between the actors was immediately and officially dissolved.

18:47.620 --> 18:47.840
Yeah.

18:48.500 --> 18:53.560
The clerics even warned them that continuing to live together in their own home constituted

18:53.560 --> 18:54.140
adultery.

18:54.140 --> 18:55.140
It's horrifying.

18:56.140 --> 19:02.020
But why do those outcomes provoke such a visceral reaction of wrongness in us?

19:02.160 --> 19:04.960
Why do we immediately recoil from those rulings?

19:05.080 --> 19:05.940
Because it's insane.

19:06.100 --> 19:06.580
It is.

19:06.700 --> 19:13.440
It is because our fundamental human intuition recognizes that behaviorism is structurally bankrupt.

19:13.860 --> 19:18.720
You simply cannot reduce a human action to merely conforming to a pattern of behavior.

19:18.720 --> 19:23.220
Internal awareness and intent are not optional add-ons.

19:23.360 --> 19:25.600
They are the core architecture of an action.

19:26.100 --> 19:32.020
Aristotle, thousands of years ago, understood this way better than the 20th century behaviorists.

19:32.180 --> 19:34.160
He called it the reason of ignorance.

19:34.460 --> 19:35.720
The reason of ignorance.

19:36.040 --> 19:36.300
Okay.

19:36.440 --> 19:37.060
Unpack that.

19:37.060 --> 19:42.540
If Hannah was genuinely ignorant of the legal gravity of the ritual she was participating

19:42.540 --> 19:50.040
in, or if the Pakistani actors were operating under the explicit shared cognitive frame of

19:50.040 --> 19:57.640
a fictional performance, their internal intent drastically diverged from the external social

19:57.640 --> 19:58.180
outcome.

19:58.420 --> 19:58.500
Yeah.

19:58.920 --> 20:04.800
The behaviorist looks at the tape and says, well, the audio pattern matches the legal requirement.

20:04.800 --> 20:06.440
Therefore, the action occurred.

20:06.820 --> 20:12.720
But we know that an action without the animating force of intent is just empty physics.

20:12.940 --> 20:13.060
Okay.

20:13.160 --> 20:16.700
Let me play devil's advocate here because I really want to push this to the breaking point.

20:16.780 --> 20:17.280
Go for it.

20:17.640 --> 20:24.700
What if the behavior doesn't just match a legal script, but it physically produces a perfect

20:24.700 --> 20:26.400
outcome by total accident?

20:27.420 --> 20:30.540
Let's say I'm sitting at a desk with a photograph of a house.

20:30.540 --> 20:37.340
I take a piece of tracing paper, and with deep concentration, I intentionally trace every

20:37.340 --> 20:39.120
line until I have a perfect replica.

20:39.240 --> 20:40.400
Hey, a deliberate action.

20:40.780 --> 20:41.020
Right.

20:41.240 --> 20:42.920
Now, imagine another scenario.

20:43.300 --> 20:44.500
I am blindfolded.

20:44.620 --> 20:48.800
I have a pen in my hand, and I am having a random muscle spasm.

20:49.000 --> 20:51.680
My hand is just violently jerking around on the paper.

20:52.280 --> 20:59.380
But, against all astronomical odds, the ink happens to land in the exact shape of that identical

20:59.380 --> 20:59.860
house.

20:59.860 --> 21:02.260
A one-in-a-trillion chance.

21:02.380 --> 21:02.820
Exactly.

21:03.520 --> 21:09.000
To a pure behaviorist, who only looks at the final output, they both produced a house.

21:10.020 --> 21:14.580
Can behaviorism actually differentiate between the argus and the spasm?

21:14.860 --> 21:19.500
That is the exact thought experiment that shattered the behaviorist consensus.

21:20.540 --> 21:23.840
Philosophers like Larry Wright really grappled with this paradox.

21:23.840 --> 21:31.380
How do you objectively distinguish between purposeful action and cosmic coincidence if you absolutely

21:31.380 --> 21:33.040
refuse to look inside the mind?

21:33.160 --> 21:33.360
Right.

21:33.500 --> 21:33.980
You can't.

21:34.060 --> 21:39.640
To illustrate how impossible this is, philosophers introduced the chess-playing Martian scenario.

21:39.740 --> 21:40.580
I love this one.

21:40.580 --> 21:45.440
Imagine an alien spacecraft lands on Earth.

21:45.440 --> 21:46.800
A Martian steps out.

21:47.240 --> 21:57.900
This creature has absolutely no conceptual framework for games, no understanding of rules, no concept of human competition, and no idea what winning or losing even means.

21:57.900 --> 21:59.640
It's just a totally alien mind.

21:59.980 --> 22:00.300
Right.

22:00.300 --> 22:06.000
The Martian happens to sit down at a table across from a human chess grandmaster.

22:06.380 --> 22:07.980
The grandmaster moves a pawn.

22:08.460 --> 22:16.460
The Martian, perhaps responding to a random electromagnetic fluctuation in its environment, reaches out and moves the knight.

22:16.460 --> 22:17.440
Just a twitch.

22:17.600 --> 22:18.340
Just a twitch.

22:18.660 --> 22:19.820
The grandmaster counters.

22:20.280 --> 22:27.500
The Martian, again randomly twitching, happens to execute the exact mathematically perfect counter move.

22:28.060 --> 22:34.860
This continues for 40 moves until the Martian accidentally delivers a flawless checkmate.

22:35.660 --> 22:38.840
The question is, is the Martian playing chess?

22:39.360 --> 22:39.800
No.

22:40.280 --> 22:41.040
Of course not.

22:41.340 --> 22:45.320
It's just manipulating carved pieces of wood on a checkered board.

22:45.320 --> 22:48.080
It has no idea what a bishop is or what a king is.

22:48.280 --> 22:48.760
Precisely.

22:48.960 --> 22:55.940
And this destroys behaviorism because it highlights the monumental difference between conforming to a rule and following a rule.

22:56.040 --> 22:58.000
Ah, conforming versus following.

22:58.120 --> 22:58.420
Yes.

22:59.260 --> 23:04.260
The Martian's physical movements conform to the rules of chess by pure statistical anomaly.

23:04.840 --> 23:13.440
But to follow a rule requires a conscious entity to deliberately pattern their ongoing behavior after an internal representation of that rule.

23:13.440 --> 23:15.660
It requires a mind holding a goal.

23:15.660 --> 23:25.840
The behaviorists tried their hardest to banish the ghost in the machine, but it turns out the ghost is the only thing that makes the machine's movements meaningful.

23:25.840 --> 23:30.020
Okay, so, the behaviorist detour was a complete failure.

23:31.100 --> 23:32.380
We are forced to retreat.

23:33.060 --> 23:38.800
We have to admit that our internal invisible intentions must be the cause of our physical actions.

23:38.960 --> 23:40.020
We need the ghost.

23:40.180 --> 23:40.980
We need the ghost.

23:41.080 --> 23:41.300
Yeah.

23:41.300 --> 23:51.040
But, and this is a massive but, we are still shackled to that broken Newtonian billiard ball theory of cause and effect.

23:51.160 --> 23:51.400
Yeah.

23:51.520 --> 23:56.100
We still have to explain how the mental cue stick hits the physical cue ball.

23:56.140 --> 23:58.000
Right, the physics still don't make sense.

23:58.000 --> 24:06.440
And trying to cram human intention into Newtonian physics leads to my absolute favorite philosophical trap in this entire deep dive.

24:06.960 --> 24:10.180
It is known as the problem of the wayward causal chain.

24:10.280 --> 24:11.720
Ah, yes.

24:12.040 --> 24:16.320
Roderick Chisholm's legendary thought experiment about the nervous nephew.

24:17.160 --> 24:20.860
This is where the old model of physics finally just breaks in half.

24:21.060 --> 24:22.720
It is so darkly brilliant.

24:22.940 --> 24:25.120
Okay, let's set the stage for this one.

24:25.120 --> 24:26.680
Imagine a young man.

24:27.000 --> 24:29.660
He has an extremely wealthy elderly uncle.

24:30.480 --> 24:36.240
The nephew is greedy, he's impatient, and he decides he wants his massive inheritance right now.

24:36.520 --> 24:37.740
A classic motive.

24:38.020 --> 24:38.420
Classic.

24:39.020 --> 24:45.820
He sits in his apartment and forms a crystal clear, deeply conscious, premeditated intention.

24:46.340 --> 24:50.080
I am going to get in my car, drive to my uncle's house, and run him over.

24:50.720 --> 24:52.260
He has the motive, he has the plan.

24:52.440 --> 24:54.860
So he goes downstairs and gets behind the wheel.

24:54.860 --> 24:56.480
The intention has formed.

24:57.160 --> 24:57.560
Right.

24:57.980 --> 25:05.020
But the sheer weight of forming this dark, murderous intention completely overwhelms his nervous system.

25:05.540 --> 25:07.380
He becomes incredibly agitated.

25:07.900 --> 25:09.540
He is sweating profusely.

25:09.680 --> 25:11.280
His hands are violently shaking.

25:11.740 --> 25:13.640
His heart is hammering in his chest.

25:13.660 --> 25:15.280
He's having a full panic attack.

25:15.460 --> 25:16.000
Exactly.

25:16.000 --> 25:23.860
He is so consumed and distracted by the horror of his own plan that he completely loses control of his vehicle.

25:24.640 --> 25:31.420
The car violently swerves off the road, hops the curb, and accidentally plows into a random pedestrian walking on the sidewalk.

25:31.420 --> 25:40.580
The nephew, horrified, jumps out of the wrecked car, looks down, and realizes the pedestrian he just killed is his rich uncle.

25:40.580 --> 25:42.000
The trap is set.

25:42.200 --> 25:42.320
Yeah.

25:42.400 --> 25:46.020
So we have to ask the ultimate philosophical and legal question here.

25:46.480 --> 25:48.360
Did the nephew murder his uncle?

25:48.620 --> 25:50.380
Did he perform the action of killing?

25:50.800 --> 25:59.880
See, if you are forced to use the standard billiard ball model of causality, the horrifying answer is technically yes.

26:00.080 --> 26:00.400
Right.

26:00.700 --> 26:01.700
The math checks out.

26:01.820 --> 26:02.380
It does.

26:02.500 --> 26:02.700
Yeah.

26:02.700 --> 26:04.100
Let's trace the physics.

26:05.320 --> 26:08.380
The nephew had an internal intention to kill his uncle.

26:09.600 --> 26:16.280
That intention, the cue stick, struck his nervous system, causing a state of severe agitation, the cue ball.

26:16.940 --> 26:27.260
That agitation caused his hands to jerk the steering wheel, which caused the car to swerve, which caused the blunt force trauma that resulted in the death of the uncle.

26:27.800 --> 26:29.220
The eight ball in the corner pocket.

26:29.240 --> 26:30.740
The causal chain is unbroken.

26:31.140 --> 26:31.600
Exactly.

26:31.600 --> 26:35.020
Event A caused event B caused event C.

26:35.560 --> 26:37.860
Philosophers were terrified by this loophole.

26:38.320 --> 26:45.440
Arthur Danto, a highly influential thinker, tried to patch the hole by introducing a new requirement called semantic fit.

26:45.640 --> 26:46.420
Semantic fit?

26:46.520 --> 26:46.700
Yeah.

26:46.980 --> 26:56.900
He argued that an event only qualifies as a genuine action if the final real-world outcome matches the original semantic representation in the person's bed.

26:57.420 --> 26:59.020
He thought this would save the theory.

26:59.020 --> 27:01.900
But apply Danto's rule to the nephew.

27:02.420 --> 27:05.240
The nephew's internal representation was a dead uncle.

27:05.780 --> 27:08.520
The final outcome in the real world is a dead uncle.

27:08.960 --> 27:11.140
The semantic fit is literally perfect.

27:11.540 --> 27:12.180
Exactly.

27:12.720 --> 27:24.820
Yet every single fiber of our human intuition screams that this was a vehicular manslaughter wrapped in a cosmic irony, not a successful execution of a murder plot.

27:24.820 --> 27:25.820
Why?

27:26.200 --> 27:28.280
Because the nephew lost control.

27:28.780 --> 27:29.280
Yes.

27:29.600 --> 27:34.760
The intention started the chain reaction, but it completely disconnected midstream.

27:34.920 --> 27:36.740
The cue stick slipped off the ball.

27:36.920 --> 27:38.420
That is the crucial insight.

27:38.420 --> 27:43.080
The intention did not actively guide the behavior to its completion.

27:43.400 --> 27:48.180
It acted as a blind, momentary trigger, not an ongoing constraint.

27:48.800 --> 27:51.340
Think back to your tracing example with the house.

27:51.580 --> 28:03.060
If you want to trace the picture, your intention to trace has to continuously, actively guide the micro-movements of your hand, millimeter by millimeter, correcting for errors in real time.

28:03.060 --> 28:04.960
Right, I'm watching the line as I draw it.

28:05.020 --> 28:05.500
Exactly.

28:05.940 --> 28:10.940
It cannot just violently shove your hand across the desk and hope the ink miraculously forms a roof.

28:11.180 --> 28:14.220
The standard causal model only allows for pushing.

28:14.620 --> 28:17.600
It has absolutely no mechanism for guiding.

28:18.020 --> 28:20.340
So philosophy has essentially hit a brick wall.

28:20.820 --> 28:26.780
The ancient physics don't work, Newtonian physics don't work, and behaviorism is a joke.

28:27.320 --> 28:28.840
Where do we even go from here?

28:28.840 --> 28:36.880
The brilliant pivot here is that we have to stop talking to philosophers and physicists who study moving mass.

28:37.380 --> 28:37.460
Right.

28:37.620 --> 28:40.960
We have to cross the campus and talk to communications engineers.

28:41.380 --> 28:44.080
We have to dive into information theory.

28:44.580 --> 28:47.080
This is where the paradigm shift actually happens.

28:47.240 --> 28:47.800
It is.

28:48.200 --> 28:55.080
In the 1940s, a mathematician named Claude Shannon, working at Bell Labs, developed information theory.

28:55.080 --> 28:59.020
He wasn't trying to solve the riddle of free will.

28:59.420 --> 29:08.720
He was just trying to figure out how to transmit voice messages over long copper telephone lines without the signal turning into static.

29:09.060 --> 29:16.120
But it turns out the mathematics of signal transmission are the exact tools we need to solve the philosopher's dead end.

29:16.620 --> 29:17.060
Completely.

29:17.060 --> 29:22.560
Because information theory completely abandons the idea of objects crashing into each other.

29:22.900 --> 29:24.780
It doesn't care about force or mass.

29:24.980 --> 29:30.220
It cares entirely about tracking the flow of a signal from a source to a destination.

29:30.580 --> 29:33.660
Yeah, let's ground this math in a story because it can get abstract.

29:34.240 --> 29:41.340
There is a fantastic example formulated by the philosopher Fred Dretzky involving an office worker named Herman.

29:41.880 --> 29:43.320
Oh, I'll walk through this one.

29:43.320 --> 29:46.880
So imagine a corporate office with eight employees.

29:47.760 --> 29:56.520
The boss comes in and says, hey, one of you has to stay late on Friday to do this incredibly tedious, nasty inventory task.

29:56.820 --> 29:59.820
I don't care who, you figure it out and let me know.

29:59.900 --> 30:01.520
Standard, terrible boss.

30:01.720 --> 30:02.200
Exactly.

30:02.200 --> 30:13.620
So the eight employees sit in a conference room and they decide to make it fair by flipping coins to eliminate people until there's only one loser left.

30:13.920 --> 30:15.840
Let's do the math on this really quick.

30:16.120 --> 30:17.620
You start with eight possibilities.

30:18.020 --> 30:22.160
You flip a coin, heads or tails, and you eliminate half the room.

30:22.940 --> 30:23.640
Now you have four possibilities.

30:24.300 --> 30:25.540
At least one bit of information.

30:25.800 --> 30:26.020
Right.

30:26.280 --> 30:28.960
You flip again, eliminating half the remaining people.

30:29.340 --> 30:30.580
Now you have two possibilities.

30:30.680 --> 30:31.460
That's two bits.

30:31.460 --> 30:35.420
You flip a third time and you're left with one single loser.

30:35.840 --> 30:36.680
That's three bits.

30:36.780 --> 30:42.440
It takes exactly three bits of information to reduce eight possibilities down to a single certainty.

30:43.180 --> 30:45.940
And the loser, sadly, is Herman.

30:46.380 --> 30:47.360
Poor Herman.

30:47.980 --> 30:50.740
So we have established our starting point.

30:50.880 --> 30:58.920
We have a source, the coin flipping process in the conference room, that has successfully generated exactly three bits of information.

30:58.920 --> 31:08.060
Now, that information has to flow across the environment to reach its destination, which is the boss's desk.

31:08.240 --> 31:08.600
Right.

31:08.800 --> 31:12.880
So let's look at scenario A, which we'll call the careful messenger.

31:12.880 --> 31:21.280
The employees write Herman on a piece of paper, fold it up, and hand it to a very diligent, careful intern.

31:21.800 --> 31:26.860
The intern walks down the halls, knocks on the boss's door, and hands over the note.

31:27.260 --> 31:29.600
The bog opens it and reads Herman.

31:29.600 --> 31:30.600
Perfect transmission.

31:30.600 --> 31:31.040
Perfect transmission.

31:31.320 --> 31:31.720
Exactly.

31:32.440 --> 31:40.060
In this scenario, the three bits of information generated at the source perfectly equal the three bits of information received at the destination.

31:40.740 --> 31:41.920
The flow is unbroken.

31:41.920 --> 31:46.760
But then Dretzky introduces scenario B, which is the careless messenger.

31:47.300 --> 31:49.860
The exact same process happens in the conference room.

31:50.040 --> 31:50.660
Herman loses.

31:51.180 --> 31:55.280
They write his name on a note and hand it to a careless, easily distracted intern.

31:56.060 --> 32:03.440
As this intern is walking down the hall, he trips and the note slips out of his hand and falls directly into an active paper shredder.

32:03.780 --> 32:04.700
The note is gone.

32:05.560 --> 32:06.040
Destroyed.

32:06.280 --> 32:07.620
The intern panics.

32:07.620 --> 32:13.640
He knows there are eight employees in that department, but he has absolutely no idea who lost the coin toss.

32:14.180 --> 32:16.360
He knows he'll be fired if he doesn't deliver a name.

32:17.120 --> 32:20.860
So in a moment of desperation, he decides to just guess.

32:21.500 --> 32:24.680
He pulls out a blank piece of paper, randomly writes,

32:24.980 --> 32:28.540
Herman, walks into the boss's office, and hands it over.

32:29.260 --> 32:30.600
Now look at the end result here.

32:30.940 --> 32:32.420
The boss opens the note.

32:32.800 --> 32:33.540
It says Herman.

32:33.540 --> 32:38.300
The observable outcome in the room is identical to scenario A.

32:38.820 --> 32:41.260
The boss believes Herman is doing the inventory.

32:41.980 --> 32:46.840
But structurally, something is profoundly, deeply broken here.

32:47.120 --> 32:51.880
Because absolutely zero information actually flowed from the source to the destination.

32:52.580 --> 32:56.220
The three bits of information from the coin flip died in the shredder.

32:56.860 --> 33:01.940
The Herman that arrived on the desk was generated entirely by the intern's random panic.

33:01.940 --> 33:10.480
Information theory gives us the precise mathematical vocabulary to articulate why scenario B feels like a lie, even though the outcome is correct.

33:11.140 --> 33:16.940
In Shannon's framework, there are two primary enemies that destroy the flow of information across a channel.

33:17.500 --> 33:19.820
They are called equivocation and noise.

33:20.160 --> 33:22.900
These are critical concepts, so let's define them carefully.

33:23.060 --> 33:23.300
Sure.

33:23.300 --> 33:31.760
Equivocation is information that is successfully generated at the source, but gets lost or destroyed in transit.

33:32.140 --> 33:33.940
It never reaches the destination.

33:34.180 --> 33:35.920
It is a drop in the signal.

33:36.900 --> 33:39.740
Noise, on the other hand, is the exact opposite.

33:40.520 --> 33:46.420
Noise is rogue information that appears at the destination, but it did not originate from the source.

33:46.540 --> 33:49.680
It was introduced into the channel somewhere along the journey.

33:49.680 --> 33:53.300
I think the clearest way to visualize this is through a car radio.

33:53.860 --> 33:54.940
Oh, that's a good analogy.

33:55.140 --> 33:55.240
Yeah.

33:55.320 --> 34:00.220
Imagine you are driving and you tune into the local news station.

34:00.880 --> 34:06.340
The announcer at the station, who is the source, says, there will be rain on Sunday.

34:06.900 --> 34:12.660
But your car is driving through a tunnel and the antenna picks up a bunch of static, so you hear, there will be rain on Sunday.

34:13.180 --> 34:14.360
Snap, crackle, pop.

34:14.600 --> 34:14.900
Right.

34:14.900 --> 34:17.280
That static is pure noise.

34:17.800 --> 34:21.500
It is extra garbage information that the announcer never spoke.

34:22.360 --> 34:27.060
However, despite the noise, the core message survives.

34:27.900 --> 34:30.180
You still noted an umbrella on Sunday.

34:30.900 --> 34:34.260
The channel has noise, but it does not have equivocation.

34:34.660 --> 34:36.040
The signal pushed through.

34:36.240 --> 34:38.720
But consider a slight variation on that.

34:38.720 --> 34:45.580
What if that burst of static happens at the exact millisecond the announcer is speaking the day of the week?

34:46.180 --> 34:49.980
The radio broadcasts, there will be rain on loud static day-day.

34:50.380 --> 34:52.520
Now you have a catastrophic problem.

34:52.660 --> 34:53.120
Exactly.

34:53.440 --> 34:54.080
Is it Sunday?

34:54.340 --> 34:54.900
Is it Monday?

34:55.040 --> 34:55.540
You don't know.

34:56.000 --> 35:02.600
The static, the noise, was so perfectly placed that it obliterated the crucial difference between the two days.

35:03.120 --> 35:06.800
The information generated at the source was destroyed in transit.

35:06.800 --> 35:11.220
In this case, the noise directly caused equivocation.

35:11.900 --> 35:12.980
The signal is dead.

35:13.920 --> 35:16.480
This is the moment where all the pieces lock together.

35:17.000 --> 35:24.220
We can take this exact mathematics from telephone lines and radio antennas and apply it directly to the nervous nephew in his car.

35:24.320 --> 35:25.540
Yes, let's map it out.

35:25.700 --> 35:25.960
Okay.

35:26.400 --> 35:31.500
The nephew's conscious, murderous intention inside his brain is the source.

35:31.500 --> 35:36.640
The steering wheel and the physical trajectory of the car are the destination.

35:37.760 --> 35:39.720
The intention generates the signal.

35:40.420 --> 35:42.460
Turn the wheel 15 degrees to the right.

35:42.780 --> 35:43.420
Accelerate.

35:43.900 --> 35:44.760
Aim for the uncle.

35:44.900 --> 35:46.560
That's the clear message.

35:47.060 --> 35:49.420
The signal starts traveling down his nervous system.

35:49.420 --> 35:54.460
But suddenly, his extreme existential panic kicks in.

35:55.120 --> 36:04.500
The sweating, the violent shaking of his hands, the erratic hammering of his heart, all of that severe physiological agitation is noise.

36:05.240 --> 36:10.340
It is massive amounts of rogue kinetic energy flooding the channel.

36:10.340 --> 36:14.980
And it is a level of noise that causes total, catastrophic equivocation.

36:15.800 --> 36:22.200
The precise, guided signal of his intention turned 15 degrees right is completely drowned out by the shaking of his hands.

36:22.680 --> 36:24.800
The signal never reaches the steering wheel.

36:25.320 --> 36:29.480
The structural link between the mind and the environment is severed.

36:29.980 --> 36:33.780
The nervous shaking was the careless messenger dropping the note in the shredder.

36:33.900 --> 36:34.380
Exactly.

36:34.380 --> 36:39.580
The uncle still died at the end of the timeline, just like the boss still got a note saying Herman.

36:40.800 --> 36:47.200
But the specific information encoded in the nephew's original intention did not flow into the physical action.

36:47.960 --> 36:51.800
The physical outcome was generated purely by the random noise of his panic.

36:52.660 --> 36:54.940
It was a dark, cosmic coincidence.

36:55.500 --> 36:56.100
Precisely.

36:56.340 --> 37:00.760
And this is how information theory finally solves the problem of action.

37:00.760 --> 37:15.080
It proves mathematically that a true, voluntary action, a wink, and not just a blink, requires an unbroken, continuous flow of information from the cognitive source to the behavioral terminus.

37:15.160 --> 37:16.020
It's all about the flow.

37:16.600 --> 37:22.020
Causality in human behavior is not a billiard ball bouncing off another billiard ball.

37:22.020 --> 37:31.560
It is an ongoing, sustained signal that continuously constrains, corrects, and guides the physical body through space and time.

37:31.800 --> 37:39.840
If that signal is scrambled by noise or lost to equivocation, the resulting physical movement is divorced from your agency.

37:40.560 --> 37:43.440
It is an event, but it is not your action.

37:43.660 --> 37:49.820
So using information theory, we have completely torn down and rebuilt the mechanical model of how we act.

37:49.840 --> 37:50.520
We really have.

37:50.520 --> 37:54.680
But the implications of this shift don't stop at our physical movements.

37:55.100 --> 38:04.480
Because if our mechanical models of how we move our bodies are fundamentally broken, it turns out our mechanical models of how we process our feelings are equally disastrous.

38:05.420 --> 38:14.440
And this leads us directly into the second massive paradigm shift of this journey, moving from the physics of action into the complex world of human emotion.

38:14.440 --> 38:20.420
It is a perfect transition, because the exact same error occurred in both fields.

38:21.360 --> 38:34.580
Just as physicists and philosophers used to think of actions as billiard balls crashing into each other, psychologists and the general public have spent the last century thinking of emotions using a hydraulic model.

38:34.720 --> 38:37.200
Ah, the hydraulic model.

38:37.200 --> 38:44.000
Yeah, this is an incredibly pervasive idea that was heavily championed and popularized by Sigmund Freud.

38:44.160 --> 38:45.760
The whole pressure cooker model.

38:45.840 --> 38:46.420
Exactly.

38:47.080 --> 38:56.440
The hydraulic metaphor posits that human emotions, specifically intense negative emotions like anger, rage, or deep sadness function,

38:56.440 --> 39:02.440
like volatile fluids trapped under immense pressure inside a closed tank within your mind.

39:02.600 --> 39:03.920
Okay, I can picture that.

39:03.920 --> 39:12.380
The theory suggests that as you experience stress or frustration in your life, that internal tank slowly fills up with rage fluid.

39:12.880 --> 39:15.180
The pressure builds against the walls of your psyche.

39:15.600 --> 39:20.980
And the core tenet of this model is that if you do not actively open a valve and let it all out,

39:21.280 --> 39:29.300
the pressure will continue to build until you suffer a catastrophic psychological explosion, resulting in a breakdown or sudden violence.

39:29.300 --> 39:34.220
And this mechanism of releasing the pressure is what we call catharsis.

39:34.340 --> 39:34.740
Yes.

39:35.020 --> 39:40.940
This idea is so deeply baked into our modern culture that we don't even question it anymore.

39:41.160 --> 39:43.160
You hear the vocabulary everywhere.

39:43.340 --> 39:46.200
A friend calls you and says, I just need to vent.

39:46.900 --> 39:49.580
We tell people who are grieving, just have a good cry.

39:49.720 --> 39:51.120
You need to get it out of your system.

39:51.180 --> 39:51.380
Right.

39:51.460 --> 39:52.140
It's everywhere.

39:52.140 --> 40:09.840
There is literally an entire booming industry of smash rooms where you pay $50 to put on safety goggles and destroy televisions and plates with a baseball bat specifically to, quote, release your anger.

40:10.160 --> 40:11.700
It's a huge business.

40:11.700 --> 40:18.580
And the reason it's so popular is because it feels so intuitively true to our physical experience.

40:19.240 --> 40:27.540
When I'm absolutely furious about something, my chest feels tight, my face is flushed, my heart is racing, I actually feel like a pressure cooker about to blow a gasket.

40:27.700 --> 40:29.580
The physical symptoms are very real.

40:29.720 --> 40:29.920
Right.

40:30.280 --> 40:39.940
And my immediate overwhelming instinct is to call a sympathetic friend and just unleash a 20-minute high-volume rant.

40:39.940 --> 40:42.840
I feel like I had to drain the tank to survive.

40:43.160 --> 40:49.720
The physical sensation is very real, but the mechanical metaphor we use to explain it is completely backward.

40:50.340 --> 40:53.660
And the empirical data is devastating to Freud's theory.

40:54.120 --> 40:54.860
Wait, really?

40:55.220 --> 40:55.680
Oh, yeah.

40:56.460 --> 41:06.800
Decades of rigorous psychological and physiological studies have repeatedly demonstrated that this hydraulic model of catharsis is scientifically incoherent.

41:06.800 --> 41:23.300
When researchers take subjects, deliberately induce a state of anger, and then provide them with an outlet to vent their frustration, like giving them a punching bag and telling them to think about the person who angered them, the subjects do not get less angry.

41:23.480 --> 41:24.920
Their tank does not drain.

41:25.100 --> 41:25.440
Wow.

41:25.700 --> 41:27.920
In fact, exactly the opposite happens.

41:27.920 --> 41:47.040
Hold on.

41:47.300 --> 41:50.040
Let me make sure I am fully understanding the magnitude of this.

41:50.040 --> 42:02.260
If I am furious at my boss, and I go to the gym and savagely beat a heavy bag for 20 minutes while screaming in my head, I am not actually draining any anger.

42:02.820 --> 42:08.720
Every therapist or self-help article that told me to get it out was giving me biologically harmful advice.

42:09.260 --> 42:11.200
Mathematically and biologically, yes.

42:11.600 --> 42:13.680
You are not opening a relief valve.

42:13.680 --> 42:21.640
The paper we are analyzing introduces a complex mathematical framework to explain exactly why venting fails.

42:22.120 --> 42:32.780
It proves that indulging the intense emotion through explosive catharsis actually amplifies the persistence of that emotion through resonant feedback loops.

42:32.960 --> 42:37.040
I read an analogy for this in the material that completely rewired my brain.

42:37.040 --> 42:40.500
Venting your anger isn't like draining a tank of water.

42:40.660 --> 42:46.080
It is like trying to stop a violent whirlpool by grabbing the paddle and vigorously stirring it.

42:46.180 --> 42:51.900
That is the most accurate visualization possible, and this is the moment we introduce the RSVP model.

42:51.960 --> 42:53.040
Okay, RSVP.

42:53.260 --> 42:57.080
It stands for the Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum.

42:57.080 --> 43:03.720
It is a dense acronym, but it represents a beautiful, elegant shift in how we view the brain.

43:03.720 --> 43:09.940
We have to permanently discard the image of the mind as a rigid metal tank holding fluid.

43:10.680 --> 43:16.540
Instead, we have to start visualizing the mind as a vast, continuous, topological landscape.

43:17.020 --> 43:22.600
A flowing, dynamic terrain defined by interacting fields of energy.

43:22.860 --> 43:24.480
Okay, let's explore this landscape.

43:24.720 --> 43:31.020
Let's unpack the RSVP model piece by piece, because once you see the mind this way, you can't unsee it.

43:31.020 --> 43:37.320
Walk me through the three foundational mathematical fields that construct this terrain of human consciousness.

43:38.260 --> 43:45.780
The RSVP model proposes that every cognitive state you experience is an emergent property of three distinct interacting fields.

43:46.400 --> 43:47.860
First, you have the scalar field.

43:48.380 --> 43:53.360
In layman's terms, think of this as your capacity, or your raw potential for action.

43:54.040 --> 43:59.100
It is the amount of metabolic and cognitive resource currently available in your brain.

43:59.100 --> 44:00.840
Okay, capacity, like a battery.

44:01.340 --> 44:02.840
Yeah, exactly like a battery.

44:03.160 --> 44:05.140
Second, you have the vector field.

44:05.820 --> 44:09.440
A vector requires direction, so think of this as flow.

44:09.560 --> 44:13.980
It represents the directional momentum of your attention, your thoughts, and your behavior.

44:14.720 --> 44:18.380
Where is your mental energy pointing, and how fast is it moving there?

44:18.440 --> 44:19.360
Flow, got it.

44:19.540 --> 44:21.620
And third, you have the entropy field.

44:22.400 --> 44:28.860
Entropy is a measure of disorder, so in this landscape, it represents chaos or local uncertainty.

44:29.780 --> 44:33.520
How unpredictable is the environment you are currently navigating?

44:34.020 --> 44:37.440
So we have a landscape built out of capacity, flow, and chaos.

44:38.180 --> 44:45.780
How do those abstract physics terms translate into the very real feeling of being sad or angry or joyful?

44:46.560 --> 44:50.180
Where do the actual emotions live in this terrain?

44:50.180 --> 44:54.280
In the RSVP model, an emotion is not an object you possess.

44:54.860 --> 44:55.860
It is not a noun.

44:56.180 --> 44:58.000
An emotion is an attractor basin.

44:58.200 --> 44:59.480
An attractor basin?

44:59.480 --> 44:59.840
Yes.

45:00.080 --> 45:04.960
It is a literal valley or depression that forms in the topological landscape of your mind.

45:05.540 --> 45:10.580
When this specific combination of capacity, flow, and chaos interacts, the terrain warps.

45:11.100 --> 45:16.240
And when your attention and cognitive energy get pulled down into one of these deep valleys by gravity,

45:16.240 --> 45:18.940
you subjectively experience an emotion.

45:19.220 --> 45:20.660
That makes so much sense.

45:20.660 --> 45:29.800
The researchers translate those three mathematical fields into three highly familiar psychological dimensions to help us map the valleys.

45:30.120 --> 45:33.580
They are arousal, valence, and dominance.

45:34.060 --> 45:36.600
Okay, I know these terms from basic psychology.

45:36.860 --> 45:39.620
Let's map them onto our new mental terrain.

45:39.880 --> 45:41.660
Let's start with arousal.

45:41.660 --> 45:48.020
In this model, arousal represents how turbulent and energetic the landscape is.

45:48.200 --> 45:52.240
It is the sheer volume of kinetic energy coursing through the system.

45:53.020 --> 45:58.880
A state of low arousal would look like a flat, calm, gently rolling plane.

45:59.740 --> 46:07.140
High arousal means the terrain is violent, incredibly steep slopes, jagged cliffs, and fast-moving currents of energy.

46:07.300 --> 46:08.080
And valence.

46:08.080 --> 46:13.480
Valence represents the direction of the flow relative to your personal internal goals.

46:14.040 --> 46:18.200
Are you being pushed toward something beneficial or dragged toward something harmful?

46:18.840 --> 46:22.640
Positive valence means the flow of the landscape aligns with what you want.

46:23.080 --> 46:28.720
Negative valence means the current is actively pushing you away from your goals or toward a threat.

46:28.820 --> 46:29.880
And what about dominance?

46:30.120 --> 46:32.360
That one always feels a bit abstract to me.

46:32.360 --> 46:39.740
Dominance tracks the state of the system as a whole, specifically, whether your sphere of influence is expanding or contracting.

46:40.420 --> 46:46.920
Do you feel like you are in control, expanding your presence, and successfully navigating the terrain?

46:47.420 --> 46:52.880
Or do you feel trapped, overwhelmed, and shrinking away from an insurmountable obstacle?

46:52.880 --> 46:57.420
So, let's take these tools and go back to the anger whirlpool.

46:57.840 --> 47:02.100
Let's say someone rear-ends my car and they jump out and start yelling at me.

47:02.500 --> 47:04.580
I am instantly furious.

47:05.040 --> 47:12.520
In the RSVP model, I have just been dragged into a very deep, very steep valley of negative valence.

47:12.520 --> 47:14.380
The situation is bad.

47:15.040 --> 47:16.940
The arousal is extremely high.

47:17.040 --> 47:18.140
My heart is pounding.

47:18.620 --> 47:20.440
The terrain is churning with energy.

47:21.120 --> 47:23.840
The old catharsis model tacks me on the shoulder and says,

47:23.960 --> 47:26.920
yell back at them, hit your steering wheel, release the pressure.

47:27.260 --> 47:30.420
When I actually do that, when I start screaming and venting,

47:30.720 --> 47:33.800
what is physically and mathematically happening to that valley?

47:33.980 --> 47:40.140
You are injecting massive amounts of kinetic energy directly into an already unstable system.

47:40.140 --> 47:43.100
In the language of dynamical systems and physics,

47:43.260 --> 47:46.420
you are inducing what is called a Hoff bifurcation.

47:46.740 --> 47:48.220
A Hoff bifurcation.

47:48.740 --> 47:52.400
Let's break that down, because it sounds like something that happens to a dying star,

47:52.560 --> 47:54.020
not a guy in a traffic jam.

47:54.340 --> 47:56.340
It's a profound concept, really.

47:56.960 --> 48:00.740
Imagine a simple pendulum swinging gently back and forth.

48:00.860 --> 48:02.120
It's a stable system.

48:02.920 --> 48:07.460
Now, imagine you start feeding extra energy into that pendulum

48:07.460 --> 48:10.940
by pushing it harder and harder at random intervals.

48:11.940 --> 48:14.720
Eventually, the system can't handle the extra energy.

48:15.120 --> 48:19.380
It undergoes a bifurcation, a sudden radical change in its behavior.

48:19.860 --> 48:24.880
The pendulum stops swinging smoothly and starts oscillating wildly,

48:25.160 --> 48:27.840
chaotically, just spinning out of control.

48:28.160 --> 48:29.080
So I'm the pendulum.

48:29.380 --> 48:29.680
Yes.

48:29.680 --> 48:34.040
When you are trapped in an anger valley, your mind is that pendulum.

48:35.020 --> 48:38.620
By choosing to vent, scream, or hit a punching bag,

48:38.840 --> 48:40.180
you aren't draining a tank.

48:40.340 --> 48:43.660
You are feeding violent kinetic energy into the attractor basin.

48:44.200 --> 48:48.360
The mathematics of the RSVP model prove that this influx of energy

48:48.360 --> 48:53.240
makes the walls of the emotional valley much steeper and the currents much faster.

48:53.640 --> 48:53.840
Wow.

48:54.040 --> 48:56.880
You are creating a resonant feedback loop.

48:56.880 --> 48:59.440
You are literally digging the hole deeper,

48:59.660 --> 49:04.760
trapping yourself in that aggressive state for a significantly longer period of time.

49:05.220 --> 49:06.960
This is genuinely terrifying.

49:07.880 --> 49:10.120
Because the release I feel when I yell.

49:10.280 --> 49:10.500
Yeah.

49:10.980 --> 49:13.180
It feels so good for about three seconds.

49:13.380 --> 49:17.160
Are you saying that feeling of relief is just a biological lie?

49:17.460 --> 49:21.120
It is a severe misinterpretation of your own data.

49:21.560 --> 49:23.960
What feels like a release when you scream at someone

49:23.960 --> 49:28.360
is usually just a very transient, fleeting shift in the dominance field.

49:28.820 --> 49:31.100
For one split second, by yelling louder,

49:31.480 --> 49:34.760
you feel like you are expanding, taking control of the environment,

49:34.920 --> 49:36.060
pushing the threat away.

49:36.240 --> 49:36.400
Right.

49:36.460 --> 49:38.980
But the arousal field remains violently high,

49:39.140 --> 49:41.680
and the valence field is still deeply negative.

49:42.000 --> 49:43.740
You haven't escaped the whirlpool.

49:43.900 --> 49:47.780
You've just convinced yourself that stirring it faster is a form of control.

49:47.780 --> 49:51.480
As soon as you stop yelling, the walls of the valley are still there,

49:51.600 --> 49:52.980
and they are steeper than before.

49:53.640 --> 49:54.160
Okay.

49:55.060 --> 49:58.360
You have thoroughly destroyed my coping mechanisms.

49:59.040 --> 50:02.040
But this raises a massive practical problem for me.

50:02.520 --> 50:06.400
If I am trapped at the bottom of a steep valley of a terrible emotion,

50:06.540 --> 50:07.560
say I am furious,

50:08.060 --> 50:10.840
or I am spiraling into a deep, dark depression,

50:10.840 --> 50:13.880
and I know that I shouldn't vent or thrash around

50:13.880 --> 50:16.720
because it will only induce a half bifurcation

50:16.720 --> 50:18.180
and make the valley deeper,

50:19.280 --> 50:20.860
how on earth do I get out?

50:21.180 --> 50:22.660
That's the million dollar question.

50:22.660 --> 50:26.660
Do I just have to sit perfectly still at the bottom of the pit

50:26.660 --> 50:29.960
and try to claw my way up the steep walls

50:29.960 --> 50:32.820
using sheer exhausting willpower?

50:32.960 --> 50:33.120
Yeah.

50:33.740 --> 50:37.760
Because fighting the current of a deep depression sounds impossible.

50:37.760 --> 50:39.640
It is functionally impossible,

50:40.080 --> 50:43.620
and more importantly, it is biologically unsustainable.

50:44.200 --> 50:48.420
This brings us to the second half of the paper's mathematical framework,

50:49.180 --> 50:50.320
GBSH,

50:51.040 --> 50:54.320
Geometric Bayesianism with Sparse Heuristics.

50:54.600 --> 50:57.040
I am going to need a serious translation on that one.

50:57.180 --> 50:58.380
I know it sounds intimidating,

50:58.680 --> 51:01.500
but it is actually a deeply pragmatic description

51:01.500 --> 51:03.040
of how your brain survives.

51:03.440 --> 51:06.420
The biological reality is that your brain operates

51:06.420 --> 51:10.240
under a brutally strict, unforgiving energy budget.

51:10.240 --> 51:14.400
It runs on ATP, a specific metabolic currency.

51:15.180 --> 51:19.280
Your brain accounts for roughly 20% of your daily caloric burn

51:19.280 --> 51:20.740
just to keep the lights on.

51:20.940 --> 51:22.100
That's a huge energy draw.

51:22.500 --> 51:23.020
It is.

51:23.600 --> 51:25.780
Traditional computer models of the mind

51:25.780 --> 51:29.100
assume the brain acted like a silicon supercomputer,

51:29.740 --> 51:33.100
exhaustively analyzing every single variable in a room

51:33.100 --> 51:34.440
before making a decision.

51:35.600 --> 51:39.640
But if your biological brain actually tried to brute force calculate

51:39.640 --> 51:42.360
every possible mathematical escape route

51:42.360 --> 51:43.900
out of an emotional valley,

51:44.400 --> 51:48.120
the sheer computing power required would fry your neural circuits.

51:48.600 --> 51:52.080
You would literally starve to death trying to process a bad mood.

51:52.420 --> 51:52.980
Right.

51:53.080 --> 51:56.480
I can't run a deep blue chest simulation every time I feel sand.

51:56.580 --> 51:58.260
I simply don't have the calories for it.

51:58.260 --> 51:58.980
Precisely.

51:59.480 --> 52:01.740
Because of this strict energy constraint,

52:02.240 --> 52:05.120
the brain relies heavily on sparse heuristics.

52:05.980 --> 52:08.380
A heuristic is simply a cognitive shortcut.

52:09.220 --> 52:12.140
The brain does not explore the entire topological landscape.

52:12.520 --> 52:15.660
It frantically searches for the path of least resistance.

52:16.080 --> 52:19.080
It uses sparse, incomplete data

52:19.080 --> 52:21.640
to make a good enough guess to save energy.

52:22.140 --> 52:23.860
Okay, so it cuts corners to survive.

52:23.860 --> 52:24.500
Yes.

52:25.020 --> 52:28.700
And the RSVP model reveals that there is a specific

52:28.700 --> 52:30.920
mathematically elegant solution

52:30.920 --> 52:33.940
for escaping a deep emotional valley.

52:34.300 --> 52:37.460
A method that utilizes these sparse heuristics

52:37.460 --> 52:40.220
to get you out without burning all your precious

52:40.220 --> 52:42.100
mental energy fighting the current.

52:42.440 --> 52:45.640
The solution is the process of reframing.

52:45.760 --> 52:46.900
Reframing the landscape.

52:47.100 --> 52:47.420
Yes.

52:48.000 --> 52:49.920
The key insight is that emotions

52:49.920 --> 52:53.180
and the valleys they form are highly relativistic.

52:53.180 --> 52:56.020
They do not exist in an objective vacuum.

52:56.540 --> 52:59.900
They depend entirely on your internal reference frames,

53:00.240 --> 53:03.640
the baseline expectations you brought into the environment.

53:04.140 --> 53:05.960
I think the paper had a great example for this.

53:05.980 --> 53:06.360
It did.

53:06.640 --> 53:08.940
The paper provides a perfectly simple example

53:08.940 --> 53:10.320
to illustrate this relativity.

53:10.880 --> 53:12.280
A heavy rainstorm.

53:12.700 --> 53:13.640
If I ask you,

53:14.000 --> 53:17.760
is a rainy day an inherently sad, negative event?

53:17.900 --> 53:20.680
Well, I mean, it depends entirely on my context.

53:20.680 --> 53:24.040
If I spent three weeks planning a massive beach party

53:24.040 --> 53:26.160
and I bought volleyballs and sunscreen

53:26.160 --> 53:28.700
and I wake up to a torrential downpour,

53:28.960 --> 53:31.520
then yes, a rainy day is a tragedy.

53:31.900 --> 53:33.920
It is a deep valley of negative valence.

53:34.380 --> 53:35.060
Exactly.

53:35.440 --> 53:38.180
But what if we change the observer?

53:38.180 --> 53:40.600
What if you are a local farmer

53:40.600 --> 53:44.020
who has been staring at a dying field for three months,

53:44.180 --> 53:47.160
utterly terrified that a historic drought

53:47.160 --> 53:49.120
is going to bankrupt your family

53:49.120 --> 53:50.760
and destroy your livelihood?

53:51.460 --> 53:53.320
You wake up, look out the window,

53:53.480 --> 53:56.400
and see that exact same torrential downpour.

53:56.480 --> 53:59.340
Then that rain is a literal miracle.

53:59.560 --> 53:59.760
Yeah.

53:59.840 --> 54:01.300
And crying tears of joy

54:01.300 --> 54:04.260
is a massive peak of positive valence.

54:04.400 --> 54:06.560
Pay close attention to the mechanics there.

54:06.560 --> 54:08.940
The objective meteorological stimulus,

54:09.220 --> 54:10.860
the water falling from the sky,

54:11.100 --> 54:14.000
is mathematically identical in both scenarios.

54:14.800 --> 54:17.480
The kinetic energy of the rain didn't change at all.

54:17.960 --> 54:19.740
The only variable that shifted

54:19.740 --> 54:23.280
was the internal baseline expectation of the observer.

54:23.800 --> 54:25.360
The reference frame changed.

54:25.760 --> 54:25.900
Right.

54:26.320 --> 54:28.720
So applying this to the anger whirlpool,

54:29.220 --> 54:31.020
if you are trapped at the bottom,

54:31.140 --> 54:33.060
your instinct is to fight the water

54:33.060 --> 54:35.240
or to vent and inject energy.

54:35.240 --> 54:37.340
The RSVP model says,

54:37.760 --> 54:38.920
stop fighting the water.

54:39.360 --> 54:40.920
Don't touch the arousal field.

54:41.500 --> 54:44.580
Instead, step back and examine the reference frame

54:44.580 --> 54:46.520
that created the valley in the first place.

54:46.600 --> 54:47.560
You don't fight the river.

54:47.740 --> 54:49.900
You change the shape of the riverbed itself.

54:50.180 --> 54:51.220
That is the secret.

54:51.900 --> 54:54.400
By consciously shifting your reference frame,

54:54.680 --> 54:56.240
you alter the valence field.

54:56.700 --> 54:59.840
You literally change the mathematical slope

54:59.840 --> 55:01.120
of the emotional valley

55:01.120 --> 55:03.900
without having to increase the arousal

55:03.900 --> 55:06.680
or add dangerous turbulence to the system.

55:06.860 --> 55:07.680
You tilt the board.

55:07.960 --> 55:10.580
You tilt the entire topological landscape

55:10.580 --> 55:13.000
so that the gravity that was trapping you

55:13.000 --> 55:14.440
suddenly pulls you out.

55:14.900 --> 55:17.620
You let the altered geometry of your mind

55:17.620 --> 55:18.860
do the heavy lifting

55:18.860 --> 55:21.800
rather than swimming against a raging current.

55:22.060 --> 55:23.700
I am realizing right now

55:23.700 --> 55:26.340
that this is the exact mathematical proof

55:26.340 --> 55:29.100
for why cognitive behavioral therapy is so effective.

55:29.100 --> 55:30.140
It is.

55:30.680 --> 55:33.340
CBT is entirely built around this concept.

55:34.320 --> 55:36.620
A therapist doesn't tell you to scream into a pillow

55:36.620 --> 55:38.680
about how much you hate your boss.

55:38.860 --> 55:40.940
That would be a huffed bifurcation.

55:42.040 --> 55:43.580
Instead, the therapist says,

55:43.680 --> 55:45.480
let's examine the automatic thought

55:45.480 --> 55:46.640
that put you in this valley.

55:47.260 --> 55:48.960
You believe your boss hates you

55:48.960 --> 55:50.240
because he didn't say good morning.

55:50.700 --> 55:51.880
Let's reframe.

55:52.200 --> 55:53.380
What is the evidence?

55:53.640 --> 55:55.500
Is it possible his child is sick

55:55.500 --> 55:56.500
and he was distracted?

55:56.500 --> 55:59.300
And the moment you genuinely accept

55:59.300 --> 56:00.760
that alternative perspective,

56:01.240 --> 56:02.280
the anger vanishes.

56:02.600 --> 56:05.200
You didn't burn any calories fighting the rage.

56:05.380 --> 56:07.000
You just tilted the board,

56:07.180 --> 56:08.480
the valley flattened out,

56:08.560 --> 56:10.600
and the anger ceased to exist.

56:10.760 --> 56:11.080
Yes.

56:11.240 --> 56:13.440
And the authors of the RSVP paper

56:13.440 --> 56:15.380
specifically highlight this.

56:15.860 --> 56:17.700
Effective therapies like CBT

56:17.700 --> 56:19.980
are not just nice psychological tricks.

56:20.180 --> 56:22.180
They are actively mathematically

56:22.180 --> 56:24.500
altering the copology of the mind.

56:24.500 --> 56:27.400
They are leveraging sparse heuristics

56:27.400 --> 56:29.800
to reshape the attractor basins.

56:30.320 --> 56:31.180
That is incredible.

56:31.280 --> 56:32.640
And the implications of this

56:32.640 --> 56:35.340
extend far beyond a therapist's couch.

56:35.880 --> 56:38.620
This model is currently revolutionizing

56:38.620 --> 56:40.920
how we approach artificial intelligence.

56:41.200 --> 56:43.920
If we want to build AGI artificial systems

56:43.920 --> 56:47.220
that truly think and adapt like biological brains,

56:47.440 --> 56:48.980
we cannot program them

56:48.980 --> 56:51.080
as brute force calculating machines.

56:51.080 --> 56:54.020
We need to design them with strict energy budgets,

56:54.200 --> 56:56.020
forcing them to use sparse heuristics

56:56.020 --> 56:58.860
and navigate dynamic relativistic landscapes.

56:59.260 --> 57:00.900
And think about the implications

57:00.900 --> 57:02.400
for childhood education.

57:03.380 --> 57:05.080
I mean, imagine if we taught

57:05.080 --> 57:07.640
this topological model to fifth graders

57:07.640 --> 57:10.700
instead of the outdated pressure cooker model.

57:11.440 --> 57:13.900
We spend so much time teaching kids

57:13.900 --> 57:15.340
to manage their explosions.

57:15.340 --> 57:17.300
What if we taught them

57:17.300 --> 57:20.340
that emotions are just temporary valleys

57:20.340 --> 57:22.520
based on reference frames?

57:22.940 --> 57:24.100
It would be revolutionary.

57:24.600 --> 57:25.540
We could teach them

57:25.540 --> 57:26.960
that when they feel trapped,

57:27.340 --> 57:29.280
they don't have to explode or suppress.

57:29.980 --> 57:31.140
They can pause,

57:31.680 --> 57:33.260
examine the slope of the valley,

57:33.500 --> 57:35.520
and actively compare perspectives

57:35.520 --> 57:36.900
to flatten the terrain

57:36.900 --> 57:39.160
before the spiral even starts.

57:39.480 --> 57:41.220
It would be a superpower.

57:41.440 --> 57:43.680
It would completely change human development.

57:43.680 --> 57:45.560
But if you think that is profound,

57:45.800 --> 57:48.040
we need to take one final step.

57:48.240 --> 57:48.840
Oh, there's more.

57:49.080 --> 57:51.580
Yes, because the authors of this paper

57:51.580 --> 57:54.520
take this topographical model of the mind,

57:54.720 --> 57:56.360
the idea of a landscape shifting

57:56.360 --> 57:57.700
and valleys collapsing,

57:58.040 --> 57:59.740
and they extend it to explain

57:59.740 --> 58:01.240
something truly astonishing.

58:02.080 --> 58:05.100
They argued that this exact same dynamic geometry

58:05.100 --> 58:08.180
is responsible for the evolution of human language

58:08.180 --> 58:11.160
and the very invention of formal logic.

58:11.380 --> 58:11.980
Okay, stop.

58:11.980 --> 58:13.960
You are telling me

58:13.960 --> 58:15.720
that the mathematical process

58:15.720 --> 58:17.720
that causes a feedback loop

58:17.720 --> 58:19.020
in my road rage

58:19.020 --> 58:22.300
is the exact same underlying mechanism

58:22.300 --> 58:24.220
that led human beings

58:24.220 --> 58:27.720
to invent true-false algebra centuries later.

58:28.500 --> 58:30.320
That sounds like science fiction.

58:30.880 --> 58:32.520
It sounds impossible

58:32.520 --> 58:34.260
until you look at the topology.

58:34.440 --> 58:36.680
It is all the same dynamic geometry

58:36.680 --> 58:38.860
operating on a longer timescale.

58:38.860 --> 58:40.760
To understand this,

58:40.840 --> 58:41.840
we have to look back

58:41.840 --> 58:43.820
at the origins of human language.

58:44.180 --> 58:44.320
Right.

58:44.600 --> 58:46.800
If you study many ancient, early,

58:47.000 --> 58:48.980
and indigenous languages around the world,

58:49.180 --> 58:51.020
you find that they utilized

58:51.020 --> 58:52.520
incredibly complex,

58:52.740 --> 58:55.020
highly nuanced classifier systems.

58:55.260 --> 58:57.440
What exactly is a classifier system

58:57.440 --> 58:58.520
in linguistics?

58:58.740 --> 59:00.940
It is a method of categorizing the world.

59:01.280 --> 59:03.040
In modern English, we are very lazy.

59:03.200 --> 59:04.600
We just call an object it.

59:04.600 --> 59:06.280
But in these early languages,

59:06.460 --> 59:07.540
you couldn't just say it.

59:07.740 --> 59:09.620
You had to categorize every noun

59:09.620 --> 59:11.300
based on its physical properties

59:11.300 --> 59:13.280
or its relationship to humans.

59:13.680 --> 59:16.100
You might have a specific grammatical category

59:16.100 --> 59:18.260
for objects that are long and rigid,

59:18.540 --> 59:19.160
like sticks.

59:19.600 --> 59:21.160
Another category for objects

59:21.160 --> 59:22.400
that are flat and flexible,

59:22.600 --> 59:23.220
like leaves.

59:23.880 --> 59:25.480
Another for things that are animate.

59:25.940 --> 59:27.340
Another for things that are fluid.

59:27.700 --> 59:29.000
Another for things that are edible.

59:29.000 --> 59:32.320
A single language might have dozens and dozens

59:32.320 --> 59:35.440
of these distinct, highly specific categories.

59:36.040 --> 59:38.860
Now, visualize that linguistic mind

59:38.860 --> 59:40.780
using our RSVP model.

59:41.520 --> 59:44.740
The cognitive landscape of early humans

59:44.740 --> 59:46.580
was incredibly textured.

59:47.160 --> 59:48.520
It looked like a golf ball

59:48.520 --> 59:51.440
covered in hundreds of tiny, distinct dimples.

59:52.200 --> 59:54.460
Dozens of shallow attractor basins,

59:54.640 --> 59:56.160
each representing a specific,

59:56.680 --> 59:58.700
nuanced way of interacting with the world.

59:58.700 --> 01:00:00.040
Okay, I can picture that.

01:00:00.540 --> 01:00:03.300
A very bumpy, highly complex terrain

01:00:03.300 --> 01:00:05.000
with lots of little valleys.

01:00:05.500 --> 01:00:07.280
But landscapes do not remain static.

01:00:07.760 --> 01:00:09.080
Over thousands of years,

01:00:09.300 --> 01:00:11.500
cultures experience intense evolutionary,

01:00:11.940 --> 01:00:14.000
social, and communicative pressures.

01:00:14.920 --> 01:00:16.880
Specifically, the paper points

01:00:16.880 --> 01:00:18.500
to the overwhelming influence

01:00:18.500 --> 01:00:20.260
of massive cultural narratives.

01:00:20.940 --> 01:00:22.280
The prime example they use

01:00:22.280 --> 01:00:24.260
is the spread of Abrahamic religions

01:00:24.260 --> 01:00:26.160
and their foundational stories.

01:00:26.580 --> 01:00:27.860
All right, think about the book of Genesis.

01:00:27.860 --> 01:00:30.960
It is entirely built on rigid dualities.

01:00:31.800 --> 01:00:33.660
God separates the light from the dark.

01:00:33.780 --> 01:00:35.480
He separates the earth from the waters.

01:00:35.960 --> 01:00:39.160
The creation of humanity is explicitly binary.

01:00:39.500 --> 01:00:41.400
Male and female, he created them.

01:00:41.880 --> 01:00:43.760
And then you have the story of Noah's Ark,

01:00:43.920 --> 01:00:46.500
which acts as a massive categorization event.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:48.320
The animals are saved,

01:00:48.540 --> 01:00:49.800
but they must enter the Ark

01:00:49.800 --> 01:00:52.020
strictly two by two, male and female.

01:00:52.020 --> 01:00:52.660
Exactly.

01:00:52.880 --> 01:00:55.400
These profound, culturally dominant narratives

01:00:55.400 --> 01:00:57.980
act like massive gravitational forces

01:00:57.980 --> 01:00:59.760
pulling on the cognitive landscape

01:00:59.760 --> 01:01:01.660
of the populations that adopt them.

01:01:01.880 --> 01:01:04.720
They exert an immense topological pressure.

01:01:05.120 --> 01:01:05.180
Wow.

01:01:05.580 --> 01:01:06.840
Under the heavy gravity

01:01:06.840 --> 01:01:08.360
of these dualistic stories,

01:01:08.820 --> 01:01:11.060
the complex, dimpled landscape

01:01:11.060 --> 01:01:12.800
begins to compress and warp.

01:01:13.220 --> 01:01:15.960
The system undergoes a phase transition.

01:01:15.960 --> 01:01:18.680
All of those dozens of nuanced,

01:01:18.900 --> 01:01:20.960
complex little classifier valleys

01:01:20.960 --> 01:01:23.260
are subjected to immense pressure

01:01:23.260 --> 01:01:25.000
until they begin to merge together.

01:01:25.640 --> 01:01:27.880
Over centuries, the landscape simplifies,

01:01:28.260 --> 01:01:29.780
reducing those multiple basins

01:01:29.780 --> 01:01:33.120
into a strict, incredibly deep binary structure.

01:01:33.120 --> 01:01:36.120
So the landscape transitions from a golf ball

01:01:36.120 --> 01:01:37.460
covered in little dimples

01:01:37.460 --> 01:01:40.100
into a massive, steep bowl

01:01:40.100 --> 01:01:42.520
with just two giant valleys at the bottom.

01:01:43.240 --> 01:01:44.120
Male and female.

01:01:45.140 --> 01:01:45.920
Light and dark.

01:01:46.300 --> 01:01:46.900
Good and evil.

01:01:47.160 --> 01:01:47.780
True and false.

01:01:47.900 --> 01:01:48.200
Yes.

01:01:48.760 --> 01:01:50.900
The cultural gravity forces a collapse

01:01:50.900 --> 01:01:52.900
into binary attractor basins.

01:01:53.360 --> 01:01:55.600
And here's the ultimate revelation of the paper.

01:01:56.160 --> 01:01:57.520
This gradual collapse

01:01:57.520 --> 01:01:59.860
of nuanced linguistic classifiers

01:01:59.860 --> 01:02:02.360
into strict, binary schemas

01:02:02.360 --> 01:02:04.580
laid the exact structural

01:02:04.580 --> 01:02:06.340
and biological groundwork

01:02:06.340 --> 01:02:07.820
for Boolean logic.

01:02:08.080 --> 01:02:08.900
George Boole,

01:02:09.220 --> 01:02:09.820
the mathematician

01:02:09.820 --> 01:02:11.640
who invented Boolean algebra

01:02:11.640 --> 01:02:12.940
in the 19th century.

01:02:13.720 --> 01:02:15.400
The system of ones and zeros,

01:02:15.660 --> 01:02:16.320
true and false,

01:02:16.520 --> 01:02:17.820
that literally makes

01:02:17.820 --> 01:02:19.400
every computer microchip

01:02:19.400 --> 01:02:20.500
on the planet function.

01:02:21.020 --> 01:02:21.360
Yes.

01:02:21.640 --> 01:02:22.800
The paper argues

01:02:22.800 --> 01:02:23.820
that when George Boole

01:02:23.820 --> 01:02:25.540
formalized Boolean algebra,

01:02:25.760 --> 01:02:26.800
he wasn't discovering

01:02:26.800 --> 01:02:28.140
some platonic truth

01:02:28.140 --> 01:02:29.060
floating in the ether.

01:02:29.420 --> 01:02:31.220
He was simply abstracting

01:02:31.220 --> 01:02:32.240
and formalizing

01:02:32.240 --> 01:02:34.240
a binary topological structure

01:02:34.240 --> 01:02:35.180
that had already been

01:02:35.180 --> 01:02:37.100
brutally, culturally carved

01:02:37.100 --> 01:02:38.780
into the human cognitive landscape

01:02:38.780 --> 01:02:40.580
over thousands of years

01:02:40.580 --> 01:02:41.660
of narrative pressure.

01:02:42.480 --> 01:02:43.840
Boole just wrote out the math

01:02:43.840 --> 01:02:44.940
for the Two Valley Bowl.

01:02:44.940 --> 01:02:47.220
That is absolutely staggering.

01:02:47.220 --> 01:02:48.020
I need a second

01:02:48.020 --> 01:02:49.660
to process the scale of that.

01:02:50.180 --> 01:02:51.140
You are saying

01:02:51.140 --> 01:02:53.180
that the way we categorize

01:02:53.180 --> 01:02:54.180
the world around us,

01:02:54.260 --> 01:02:55.760
the way we build our computers,

01:02:55.960 --> 01:02:57.340
the way we fundamentally

01:02:57.340 --> 01:02:59.020
process logic itself,

01:02:59.800 --> 01:03:01.700
it is all downstream

01:03:01.700 --> 01:03:03.700
of this dynamic

01:03:03.700 --> 01:03:05.540
topological folding

01:03:05.540 --> 01:03:07.060
of our mental landscape.

01:03:07.860 --> 01:03:08.960
Our computers run

01:03:08.960 --> 01:03:10.040
on ones and zeros

01:03:10.040 --> 01:03:11.840
because thousands of years ago,

01:03:12.360 --> 01:03:13.460
a story about an arc

01:03:13.460 --> 01:03:14.620
tilted the gravity

01:03:14.620 --> 01:03:15.480
of our minds.

01:03:15.480 --> 01:03:17.260
It is the closest thing

01:03:17.260 --> 01:03:18.380
I have ever seen

01:03:18.380 --> 01:03:20.060
to a unified theory

01:03:20.060 --> 01:03:20.820
of the mind.

01:03:21.240 --> 01:03:22.820
From the microscopic way

01:03:22.820 --> 01:03:23.980
a conscious intention

01:03:23.980 --> 01:03:25.340
flows like a signal

01:03:25.340 --> 01:03:26.280
to move a muscle

01:03:26.280 --> 01:03:27.000
in your arm,

01:03:27.160 --> 01:03:28.540
to the way a burst

01:03:28.540 --> 01:03:29.840
of anger spirals

01:03:29.840 --> 01:03:30.820
into a mathematical

01:03:30.820 --> 01:03:31.940
feedback loop,

01:03:32.100 --> 01:03:33.520
all the way up to the way

01:03:33.520 --> 01:03:34.860
an entire civilization

01:03:34.860 --> 01:03:36.360
invents binary logic.

01:03:36.960 --> 01:03:37.720
It is not about

01:03:37.720 --> 01:03:38.840
clockwork gears.

01:03:38.980 --> 01:03:39.800
It is not about

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:40.640
pressure cookers.

01:03:40.820 --> 01:03:42.440
It is entirely about

01:03:42.440 --> 01:03:43.720
dynamic fields,

01:03:43.960 --> 01:03:45.000
the flow of information,

01:03:45.460 --> 01:03:46.480
and the shifting constraints

01:03:46.480 --> 01:03:47.160
of the landscape

01:03:47.160 --> 01:03:47.780
we inhabit.

01:03:48.280 --> 01:03:49.440
We've covered so much

01:03:49.440 --> 01:03:49.980
ground today,

01:03:50.040 --> 01:03:50.660
I think we need to

01:03:50.660 --> 01:03:51.240
take a breath

01:03:51.240 --> 01:03:51.780
and summarize

01:03:51.780 --> 01:03:52.980
the sheer magnitude

01:03:52.980 --> 01:03:54.120
of the paradigm shift

01:03:54.120 --> 01:03:55.120
we've just walked through.

01:03:55.660 --> 01:03:56.900
We started this hour

01:03:56.900 --> 01:03:58.100
by asking a seemingly

01:03:58.100 --> 01:03:59.220
innocent question.

01:04:00.020 --> 01:04:00.880
What is the difference

01:04:00.880 --> 01:04:02.260
between a wink and a blink?

01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:03.680
And look where it took us.

01:04:03.980 --> 01:04:04.280
Right.

01:04:04.640 --> 01:04:05.660
And what we discovered

01:04:05.660 --> 01:04:06.680
is that to answer

01:04:06.680 --> 01:04:07.360
that question,

01:04:07.720 --> 01:04:08.720
we had to discard

01:04:08.720 --> 01:04:09.680
almost everything

01:04:09.680 --> 01:04:11.060
we intuitively thought

01:04:11.060 --> 01:04:12.380
we knew about causality.

01:04:13.040 --> 01:04:14.480
We are not static,

01:04:15.080 --> 01:04:16.000
inert objects

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:16.980
waiting to be pushed.

01:04:17.380 --> 01:04:18.740
We're not cue balls

01:04:18.740 --> 01:04:20.020
sitting on a felt table

01:04:20.020 --> 01:04:20.980
waiting to be struck

01:04:20.980 --> 01:04:21.640
by the cue stick

01:04:21.640 --> 01:04:22.440
of our intentions.

01:04:23.120 --> 01:04:24.320
And our minds

01:04:24.320 --> 01:04:25.280
are absolutely,

01:04:25.760 --> 01:04:26.540
unequivocally

01:04:26.540 --> 01:04:28.280
not pressure cookers

01:04:28.280 --> 01:04:29.300
holding back

01:04:29.300 --> 01:04:30.300
volatile fluids

01:04:30.300 --> 01:04:31.460
waiting to explode

01:04:31.460 --> 01:04:32.280
if we don't

01:04:32.280 --> 01:04:33.380
scream into a pillow.

01:04:33.580 --> 01:04:34.940
We are deeply embedded,

01:04:35.260 --> 01:04:36.300
profoundly sensitive,

01:04:36.580 --> 01:04:37.460
self-organizing,

01:04:37.460 --> 01:04:38.820
dynamic landscapes.

01:04:39.460 --> 01:04:40.540
Our physical actions

01:04:40.540 --> 01:04:41.320
are the result

01:04:41.320 --> 01:04:42.480
of an uninterrupted,

01:04:42.580 --> 01:04:43.660
continuous flow

01:04:43.660 --> 01:04:44.420
of information

01:04:44.420 --> 01:04:45.780
shaping and constraining

01:04:45.780 --> 01:04:46.340
our movements

01:04:46.340 --> 01:04:47.080
through space.

01:04:47.740 --> 01:04:48.520
Our emotions

01:04:48.520 --> 01:04:50.020
are not objects we hold.

01:04:50.540 --> 01:04:52.020
They are temporary valleys

01:04:52.020 --> 01:04:53.320
forming in a continuous

01:04:53.320 --> 01:04:54.340
flowing field

01:04:54.340 --> 01:04:55.140
of capacity,

01:04:55.400 --> 01:04:55.760
momentum,

01:04:55.980 --> 01:04:56.540
and chaos.

01:04:57.180 --> 01:04:58.200
We do not just

01:04:58.200 --> 01:04:59.580
blindly react to the world

01:04:59.580 --> 01:05:00.380
like a thermostat.

01:05:00.620 --> 01:05:01.880
We navigate a topology

01:05:01.880 --> 01:05:02.920
that is constantly

01:05:02.920 --> 01:05:04.060
shifting and warping

01:05:04.060 --> 01:05:04.740
based on our

01:05:04.740 --> 01:05:05.980
metabolic energy budgets

01:05:05.980 --> 01:05:07.020
and the reference frames

01:05:07.020 --> 01:05:08.020
we choose to adopt.

01:05:08.360 --> 01:05:08.980
And that leads me

01:05:08.980 --> 01:05:09.760
to a final,

01:05:09.960 --> 01:05:10.800
somewhat provocative

01:05:10.800 --> 01:05:11.620
thought that I'll

01:05:11.620 --> 01:05:12.420
leave you with

01:05:12.420 --> 01:05:13.780
as we wrap this up.

01:05:14.700 --> 01:05:15.860
We've spent all this time

01:05:15.860 --> 01:05:16.600
talking about how

01:05:16.600 --> 01:05:17.820
the landscape shapes

01:05:17.820 --> 01:05:18.440
our actions

01:05:18.440 --> 01:05:19.320
and our feelings.

01:05:19.980 --> 01:05:20.920
But think about

01:05:20.920 --> 01:05:21.780
the implications

01:05:21.780 --> 01:05:22.760
of that geometry.

01:05:23.180 --> 01:05:23.900
It's big.

01:05:24.300 --> 01:05:25.180
If everything

01:05:25.180 --> 01:05:26.160
we've talked about

01:05:26.160 --> 01:05:27.180
today is true,

01:05:27.500 --> 01:05:28.600
if our emotions,

01:05:28.920 --> 01:05:30.000
our physical actions,

01:05:30.160 --> 01:05:31.260
and even the very

01:05:31.260 --> 01:05:32.640
structure of our logic

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:34.140
are constantly

01:05:34.140 --> 01:05:35.220
being molded

01:05:35.220 --> 01:05:35.820
and shaped

01:05:35.820 --> 01:05:36.680
by the landscape

01:05:36.680 --> 01:05:37.600
of our environment

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:39.040
and the social

01:05:39.040 --> 01:05:40.040
reference frames

01:05:40.040 --> 01:05:40.880
we inhabit,

01:05:41.560 --> 01:05:42.660
then where does

01:05:42.660 --> 01:05:43.720
your environment end

01:05:43.720 --> 01:05:44.280
and where do you

01:05:44.280 --> 01:05:45.180
actually begin?

01:05:45.920 --> 01:05:46.980
If the shape

01:05:46.980 --> 01:05:47.920
of the riverbed

01:05:47.920 --> 01:05:48.860
you are flowing through

01:05:48.860 --> 01:05:49.680
is dictated

01:05:49.680 --> 01:05:50.520
by the culture,

01:05:50.800 --> 01:05:51.280
the history,

01:05:51.380 --> 01:05:51.880
and the narratives

01:05:51.880 --> 01:05:52.600
around you,

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:53.840
fighting the current

01:05:53.840 --> 01:05:54.620
might be a waste

01:05:54.620 --> 01:05:55.160
of energy.

01:05:56.200 --> 01:05:57.300
Perhaps the ultimate,

01:05:57.600 --> 01:05:59.060
truest act of free will

01:05:59.060 --> 01:06:00.460
isn't swimming harder

01:06:00.460 --> 01:06:01.300
against the water.

01:06:02.060 --> 01:06:03.080
Perhaps the ultimate

01:06:03.080 --> 01:06:03.960
act of free will

01:06:03.960 --> 01:06:05.220
is realizing you

01:06:05.220 --> 01:06:05.840
have the power

01:06:05.840 --> 01:06:06.980
to choose which river

01:06:06.980 --> 01:06:07.680
you swim in.

